[{"type":"{{","value":[["pagebanner"],["Pagebanner default.jpg"]]},"\nThe ",{"type":"'''","value":["Halifax Region"]},", focused around ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Halifax (Nova Scotia)"],["Halifax"]]},", the capital of ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Nova Scotia"]]},", is the economic hub of the province and often the first point of entry. The city offers a diversity of things to do and places to go. The surrounding area has many recreation opportunities with beaches, parks and lakes.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Cities"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Halifax (Nova Scotia)"],["Halifax"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Bedford (Nova Scotia)"],["Bedford"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Cole Harbour (Nova Scotia)"],["Cole Harbour"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Dartmouth (Nova Scotia)"],["Dartmouth"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hubbards (Nova Scotia)"],["Hubbards"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Hubley (Nova Scotia)"],["Hubley"]]}]},{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Sackville (Nova Scotia"],["Sackville"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Other destinations"]},"\n",{"type":"*","value":[" ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Peggys Cove"]]}]},"\n",{"type":"==","value":["Understand"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get in"]},"\n",{"type":"===","value":["By plane"]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Robert L. Stanfield International Airport"]}," (",{"type":"{{","value":[["IATA"],["YHZ"]]},"), located 20-30 minutes north of Halifax, provides connections to most of the major cities in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Canada"]]},", as well as some international flights to the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["United States"]]},", ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Iceland"]]}," and ",{"type":"[[","value":[["London"]]},".  \n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By car"]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":["Highway 102"]}," (sometimes referred to as the Bicentennial Highway, or Bi-High) is the main road link, connecting with the Trans-Canada Highway 104 at ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Truro (Nova Scotia)"],["Truro"]]},". The region is also the starting\/ending point for the main roads through the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Annapolis Valley"]]}," (Hwy 101), ",{"type":"[[","value":[["South Shore (Nova Scotia)"],["South Shore"]]}," (Hwy 103) and the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Eastern Shore (Nova Scotia)"],["Eastern Shore"]]}," (Hwy 7). It is roughly a three hour drive from ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Moncton"]]}," to Halifax and 3.5 hours from ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Charlottetown"]]}," to Halifax.\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By bus"]},"\nHalifax is one of the main terminals for the two bus companies that serve the ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Atlantic Provinces"]]}," â€” ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.greyhound.ca Greyhound Canada"]}]}," and ",{"type":"'''","value":[{"type":"[","value":["http:\/\/www.maritimebus.com Maritime Bus"]}]},". They provide daily bus service to other communities along Highway 102, the Trans-Canada, as well as to Charlottetown and a number of towns in ",{"type":"[[","value":[["New Brunswick"]]},".\n\n",{"type":"===","value":["By train"]},"\n",{"type":"'''","value":["VIA Rail"]}," provides service connecting Halifax to ",{"type":"[[","value":[["Montreal"]]}," three times a week. The trip takes 22 hours and also stops at Truro and Amherst.\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Get around"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["See"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Do"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Eat"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Drink"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Stay safe"]},"\n\n",{"type":"==","value":["Go next"]},"\n\n\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["IsPartOf"],["Nova Scotia"]]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["outlineregion"]]},"\n",{"type":"{{","value":[["geo"],["44.99200"],["-62.90771"],["zoom=9"]]},"\n",{"type":"[[","value":[["wikipedia:Halifax (former city)"]]}]